reviewText: Good show.

It took me a long time to decide to watch this show...and I'm soooo glad I did! This series just gets better and better with every season! Certainly, one of the highlights is Keith-Lee Castle's portrayal of "Mr. Count" Dracula.
Better than the first season. The new characters definitely made the show more enjoyable. Loved the cousins.
I LIKE A GOOD FAMILY VAMPIE SHOW

This is SO excellent!  One of the best vampire series I've seen. It is great fun to watch. Although  I got REALLY tired of the "you're only a girl" thing being said twenty thousand times (ok, that's a slight exaggeration).

This says it's a children's drama, but I find it still too much for them.  There isn't any gore or hideous creatures, but there is the threat of it.  However, my husband and I enjoyed it.  It's the story of Count Dracula's son, from his perspective, and he doesn't want to bite people and is trying to stop the war between the vampire slayers and the vampires.  Evidently, girls have no status in vampiric culture, and his older sister is in competition with him to be the better vampire.  Lots of cute moments, and Count Dracula is timid when threatened, and isn't at all what you would expect.

Ok so cheesy, yes but Renfield (Simon Ludders) very well done and reminded me of the old Young Ones series. Count Dracula  (Keith Lee Castle) was not only had the look but managed to pull off the slap stick humor the show was going for while keeping the forbodding and devilish charm that the Count should have. The real talent was in the character, Ingrid Dracula, the daughter played by Clare Thomas. I saw the show more of her characters transformation rather than Young Vladimir Dracula. Full of angst and lack of recognition she set out to become the pure evil a Dracula should be but in the end only wants her father's love. I watched every episode then watched the first season again just to put it all into perspective. Highly recommend for those that love dark humor.

LOVED IT!!!! It's kind of feels like the Addams Family or Munsters. It's a 'kid' show that is actually very progressive in some aspects. I like how the characters have depth and that there aren't just "this guy BAD"... "this guy GOOD". The good guy can have flaws and the bad guy can have virtues. The show develops over the series and more elements are added. Definitely, worth watching if you want some cheesy fun.

Season 3 is becoming less farcical as the young actors grow older. It reminds me of the aging process in the Harry Potter series. The series became more somber and grim. The charm of pre-adolescent innocence gives way to the angst of the teenage years. It's life, of course. We can't escape the process. This show is still worth watching.
